Check \(F_{is}\) and LD of microsatellite loci

Jenna Melanson

2025-06-20

We used an iterative approach to assign workers and queens to their natal colonies. First, using the software COLONY 2.0 (CITE WANG), we assigned full siblingships based on all available microsatellite data, assuming male and female monogamy and no inbreeding. A single run was carried out for each species and year, using the softwares full-likelihood approach and no siblingship size scaling or priors. Siblingships were maintained at this stage only if \(P(full sibling dyad) = 1\). A single individual from each putative colony (including non-circular colonies) was maintained for downstream analysis of microsatellite locus quality.

Ideally, high-quality markers should be in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium (e.g., inbreeding coefficient \(F_{is} = 0\)) and should be independently assorted (e.g., no linkage disequilibrium between markers). COLONY 2.0 can account for inbreeding at the population level, if specified, but \(F_{is}\) estimates for individual loci which are significantly different from the global mean \(F_{is}\) can be indicative of null alleles or other scoring errors.

To test overall \(F_{is}\) and individual locus deviations, we first calculated \(F_{is}\) for all locus, site, year, species groups using the Weir & Cockerham method in GENEPOP [insert citation].

The distributions of \(F_{is}\) estimates for each species at each site are shown below. The blue dotted line indicates \(F_{is}\) = 0, and the red dotted lines indicate \(F_{is}\) = \(\pm\) 0.1.

We employed a linear model of \(F_{is}\) estimates with locus and site as fixed predictors. We used sum-to-zero coding so that the model intercept represented the global mean \(F_{is}\) across loci, and calculated the effect of each locus and site using the emmeans package.

Below we show the computed effects of each locus for each species. The dashed black line represents \(F_{is} = 0\), and the dashed red line represents the global mean \(F_{is}\).

We iteratively removed loci which were significantly different from the global mean, starting with the locus with the greatest deviation, and re-running the model after each removal (i.e., because removing a locus with a high or low inbreeding coefficient will change the global mean and therefore all comparisons to the global mean). We did not apply an adjustment for multiple-hypothesis testing (i.e., comparison of multiple loci to the global mean \(F_{is}\)) but instead utilized a relatively stringent p-value (\(\alpha\) = 0.01) for removal of loci.

This process resulted in the removal of loci BTERN01, BTMS0104, and BTMS0059 from downstream analysis of B. mixtus and removal of BTMS0073 and BT28 for B. impatiens. \(F_{is}\) estimates for the remaining loci (n = 10 for B. mixtus, n = 13 for B. impatiens) are shown below.

Finally, we checked locus pairs for linkage disequilibrium in GENEPOP. LD values were calculated for each locus pair in each population (site and year). We applied a Bonferroni correction for multiple hypothesis testing, and flagged locus pairs which showed significant deviations in \(>2\) populations.

[[NOTE for Mike: Is there a better way of approaching this? You suggested that Bonferroni correction wasnt the best way to approach \(F_{is}\) / HWE, and I wonder if similar logic would apply here? It does seem odd to me to correct for multiple hypothesis testing and then only drop loci if they exceed the Bonferroni-correct p-value in multiple casesits common practice in the literature, but perhaps it would be better to first assess \(F_{st}\) between populations and then test LD of loci across all samples rather than individually for each population?]]

There was not strong support for linkage disequilibrium between locus pairs in B. mixtusfour pairs showed signs of LD, but only at a single site in a single year. In B. impatiens, there was strong evidence for linkage disequilibrium between BTMS0057 and BL13 (7 out of 12 populations showed significant LD following Bonferroni correction). To determine which locus to maintain, we calculated the polymorphic information content (PIC) using the package PopGenUtils (CITE PACKAGE).

We found that BTMS0057 had higher PIC in both years (PIC = 0.78) compared to BL13 (PIC = 0.47 in 2022 and 0.45 in 2023). For this reason, we chose to maintain BTMS0057 and remove BL13 from further analyses.

After locus quality screening, we calculated global \(F_{st}\) between sites to determine whether populations were in panmixia, or whether allele frequencies varied between sites. Moderate or high \(F_{st}\) between sites would suggest that final siblingship assignments should be run separately to account for differences in allele frequencies between populations.

hf_mix2023 = hf_mix2023[,!colnames(hf_mix2023) %in% c("BTMS0104", "BTMS0059", "BTERN01")]

# set individuals with partially missing data (e.g., 1 called peak, 1 unbinned peak) to NA
handle_partial = function(hf_obj){
  for (col in 2:ncol(hf_obj)){
    for (row in 1:nrow(hf_obj)){
      if (is.na(hf_obj[row, col])){
        # skip
        } else if (nchar(hf_obj[row, col]) < 6){
        hf_obj[row, col] = NA
      }
    }
  }
  return(hf_obj)
}

hf_imp2022 = handle_partial(hf_imp2022)
hf_imp2023 = handle_partial(hf_imp2023)
hf_mix2022 = handle_partial(hf_mix2022)
hf_mix2023 = handle_partial(hf_mix2023)


# calculate global Fst
fst_imp2022 <- basic.stats(hf_imp2022)$overall["Fst"]
fst_imp2023 <- basic.stats(hf_imp2023)$overall["Fst"]
fst_mix2022 <- basic.stats(hf_mix2022)$overall["Fst"]
fst_mix2023 <- basic.stats(hf_mix2023)$overall["Fst"]

The values returned were quite low (all \(F_{st} < 0.005\)), but to be doubly sure we additionally calculated Weir and Cockerhams pairwise \(F_{st}\) between each site pair.

Pairwise \(F_{st}\) values ranged from -0.002 to 0.01, again providing no substantial evidence of population differentiation. [[Last note for Mike: does this \(F_{is}\) or variation in \(F_{is}\) seem sufficiently low to you? I think you mentioned that < 0.05 or 0.1 was probably okay to ignore? I also realized that COLONY 2.0 actually can handle inbreeding/deviations from HWE, but they state in the user manual that: When inbreeding is present, a population level (average) inbreeding coefficient, equivalent to Wrights FIS, is inferred iteratively with other parameters (e.g.relationship, allele frequencies) and is used for calculating genotype frequenciesNote that, for dioecious, the non-inbreeding model is recommended except when there is strong evidence of inbreeding and the inbreeding level is high. Otherwise, using the inbreeding model for data with low or no inbreeding could slow down the computation substantially with little or no improvement for the estimation of relationships.

My conclusion from this would be that we should NOT ask the software to account for \(F_{is}\) in this case, as its probably unnecessary.

Given the very low \(F_{st}\), I also wonder whether you think it would be prudent to combine all sites for siblingship assignment (e.g., to improve estimation of allele frequencies by pooling data). The alternative would be to run the model 5* times for each population (e.g., 2 species * 2 years * 6 sites = 24 populations). I can run them on a server in parallel so time is not really an issue.

*5 times per population is a technique that I have seen repeatedly in the literatureto avoid spurious siblingships, like the ones I mentioned to you last time we met. Apparently its a common issue with COLONY, and people get around it by performing multiple runs and only maintaining the siblingships with occur with high probability in all of them. I tried it for one of my populations and sure enough all of the between-site siblingships (inviduals > 3km apart!) dropped out!]]
